1. Students can use the full range of science and engineering practices to make sense of natural phenomena and solve problems that
require understanding structure, properties and interactions of matter.
Preschool Learning and Development Expectation:
2. Recognize there are cause - and - effect relationships related to matter and energy.
Indicators of Progress                                                         Examples of High-Quality Teaching and Learning
By the end of the preschool experience (approximately 60 months/5              Experiences
years old), students may:                                                      Supportive Teaching Practices/Adults May:
a. Recognize and investigate cause - and - effect relationships in everyday    1. Provide opportunities for children to explore motion (e.g., fans and scarves,
   experiences (pushing, pulling, kicking, rolling or blowing objects).           ramps and toy cars).
b. Notice change in matter.                                                    2. Provide opportunities for children to investigate energy (e.g., heat, light,
c. Observe, describe and discuss properties of materials and transformation of    sound; investigate shadows, sort musical instruments and discuss different
   substances.                                                                    sounds made by particular movements; explore transparent properties on a
d. Seek answers to questions and test predictions using simple experiments.       light table).
                                                                               3. Provide opportunities for children to record observations in the changes of
                                                                                  matter (e.g., ice melting at the sensory table).
                                                                               4. Facilitate inquiry by asking how and why questions to encourage children to
                                                                                  make predictions and chart results.
                                                                               Examples of Learning/Children May:
                                                                               1. Discover the higher the incline in a ramp (in block area) makes the car go
                                                                                  farther.
                                                                               2. Explain that some magnets pull away and some come together.
                                                                               3. Identify when a change in matter occurs (ice melting, icicles forming, etc.).
                                                                               4. Identify how and why things move (e.g., using a balance, pushing structures
                                                                                  over, how fast different objects move).
                                                                               5. Ask questions related to why things happen.
