5. Students can use the full range of science and engineering practices to make sense of natural phenomena and solve problems that
require understanding how individual organisms are configured and how these structures function to support life, growth, behavior and
reproduction.
Preschool Learning and Development Expectation:
1. Recognize that living things have unique characteristics and basic needs that can be observed and studied.
Indicators of Progress                                                        Examples of High-Quality Teaching and Learning
By the end of the preschool experience (approximately 60 months/5             Experiences
years old), students may:                                                     Supportive Teaching Practices/Adults May:
a. Observe, describe and discuss living things.                               1. Provide opportunities for children to engage with live animals and plants
b. Observe similarities and differences in the needs of living things.           along with toy/stuffed animals and plans and photographs/pictures
c. Observe and describe how natural habitats provide for the basic needs of      throughout the classroom.
   plants and animals with respect to shelter, food, water, air and light.    2. Read books about living and nonliving things, inquire about how we know if
d. Ask and pursue questions through simple investigations and observations of    something is living or not.
   living things.                                                             3. Display worm farms, bird feeders, caterpillar/butterfly habitat, fish tank for
e. Collect, describe, and record information about living things through         observation.
   discussion, drawings, graphs, technology and charts.                       4. Watching the fish, observe and discuss the movement of the gills,
f. Identify differences between living and nonliving things.                     explaining this is how fish breathe under water.
