2. PS2:B Types of Interactions: Electric and magnetic (electromagnetic) forces    2. Systems and Systems Models: Models can be used to represent systems
   can be attractive or repulsive, and their sizes depend on the magnitudes of       and their interactions–such as inputs, processes and outputs – and energy
   the charges, currents, or magnetic strengths involved and on the distances        and matter flows within systems.
   between the interacting objects. Gravitational forces are always attractive.
   There is a gravitational force between any two masses, but it is very small
   except when one or both of the objects have large mass — e.g., Earth and
   the sun. Forces that act at a distance (electric, magnetic, and gravitational)
   can be explained by fields that extend through space and can be mapped by
   their effect on a test object (a charged object, or a ball, respectively).
